  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense in most countries and is typically addressed under criminal legislation. Money laundering involves concealing the origins of illegally obtained money by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear legal. Key points include:\n\n1. Criminal classification\n- Considered a serious financial crime\n- Prosecuted under criminal statutes\n- Can result in significant criminal penalties\n\n2. Legal framework\n- Regulated by national anti-money laundering (AML) laws\n- Often part of financial crime and proceeds of crime legislation\n- Covered by criminal codes in many jurisdictions\n\n3. Potential consequences\n- Criminal prosecution\n- Substantial fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset seizure\n\n4. International cooperation\n- Many countries have aligned their laws to combat money laundering\n- Compliance with international standards like FATF (Financial Action Task Force) recommendations\n\nThe specific legal details and penalties vary by jurisdiction, but money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity aimed at disguising the proceeds of illegal activities.",
